Aesopus claudius, or Clodius, the great, impressive tragie actor, admired by Cicero. His son (Sat. 11. iii. 239), the heir of his vast for- tunes, melted in vinegar a pearl worth 840‚000 and drank it for the whim of knowing how pearls would taste, and treated all his guests with the same kind of draught.

Afranius, a poet who flourished A. u. c. 660, who in his Latin come- dics orsabalae toqatae imitated Menander.

Agrippa, M. Vipsanius, the well-known general, friend and son—in- law of Augustus. After he had been praetor and consul, he undertook the aedileship, the lowest of the curule offices, B. c. 33, to gratify the emperor. His munificence was extremely great in the crection and adornment of public buildings and the celebration of gaines on a splen- did scale, and in large donations to the people. He was applauded in the theatre for the lavish costliness of his exhibitions. He built the Pantheon (so called), to which a porticus is attached, and also a portico in commemoration of the naval victories of Augustus, to which he gave the name Porticus Argonautarum: the latter is perhaps the one referred to Epp. ι. vi. 26. He had large estates in Sicily, probably given him by Augustus after his successes against Sextus Pompeius. Among other exploits‚ he reduced the Cantabrians Β. c. 19.

Ajux. son of Telamon, after he was defeated by Ulysses in the con- test sor the armor of Achilles, was strieken with madness‚ in which he rushed from his tent and slaughtered the sheep of the Greek army, fancying they were his enemies, and at length put an end to his own life. Agamemnon refused him sepulture. He loved the Phrygian cap- tive Tecmessa, who was given him as his prize.

Albutius, an unknown person, who poisoned his wife, and who (or another of the same name) was cruel to his slaves.
